IN THE HIGH COURT OF JUDICATURE FOR RAJASTHAN AT JODHPUR
(CIVIL APPELLATE JURISDICTION)

COMMERCIAL APPEAL NO. ________ OF 2027

IN THE MATTER OF:
National Highways Authority of India (NHAI),
Through its Project Director, PIU-Udaipur.           ...APPELLANT

VERSUS

M/s. Rajputana Infra Projects Pvt. Ltd.,
Through its Managing Director.                        ...RESPONDENT

---

APPEAL UNDER SECTION 37(1)(c) OF THE ARBITRATION AND CONCILIATION ACT, 1996 AGAINST THE ARBITRAL AWARD DATED 20.12.2026

TO,
THE HON'BLE CHIEF JUSTICE AND HIS OTHER COMPANION JUSTICES OF THE HON'BLE HIGH COURT.

THE HUMBLE APPEAL ON BEHALF OF THE APPELLANT MOST RESPECTFULLY SHOWETH:

1. THE GRIEVANCE:
That the Appellant is filing this appeal against the Arbitral Award dated 20.12.2026 passed by the Ld. Sole Arbitrator, wherein the Respondent was awarded a sum of ₹41.65 Crore along with 8.5% interest.

2. GROUNDS OF APPEAL (PATENT ILLEGALITY):

A. MISUSE OF THE HUDSON FORMULA:
The Ld. Arbitrator awarded ₹8.90 Crore towards "Loss of Profit" by simply applying the Hudson Formula. This is in direct contradiction to the law laid down by the Hon'ble Supreme Court in *Bharat Coking Coal Ltd. vs. Annapurna Construction* and *Patel Engineering Ltd. vs. North Eastern Electric Power Corporation Ltd.* (NEEPCO), which mandates that loss of profit cannot be awarded based on a formula without the claimant proving that other profitable opportunities were actually lost.

B. CONTRAVENTION OF FUNDAMENTAL POLICY:
The award ignores the explicit bar under Clause 10CC of the GCC, which restricts escalation payments for the period of delay attributable to the Contractor. The Ld. Arbitrator failed to bifurcate the delay period (78 days vs total delay), resulting in an unjust enrichment of the Respondent at the cost of the public exchequer.

C. FAILURE TO CONSIDER COUNTER-CLAIMS:
The award summarily rejected the Appellant's counter-claim for Liquidated Damages (LD) of ₹11.26 Crore despite recorded instances of slow progress not related to the site possession delay.

3. PRAYER:
It is, therefore, humbly prayed that this Hon'ble Court may be pleased to:
(i) Set aside the Arbitral Award dated 20.12.2026;
(ii) In the interim, stay the execution of the said Award;
(iii) Pass such other orders as this Hon'ble Court may deem fit.

AND FOR THIS ACT OF PARITY, THE APPELLANT SHALL EVER PRAY.

ADVOCATE FOR THE APPELLANT (NHAI)
